        <h1>Camp Williams Building 5020</h1>

        <p>The Camp Williams Building 5020 project represents Northway Construction's capability to handle complex government and military renovation work requiring security clearances, specialized building systems, and exacting standards. This substantial renovation transformed a World War II-era building into modern, functional space serving the Utah National Guard.</p>

        <p>The scope included critical structural upgrades addressing decades of building age, office space configured for contemporary military operations, modern restroom facilities meeting current codes and ADA requirements, locker room facilities for National Guard personnel, secure gun room with specialized requirements, functional kitchenette supporting daily operations, and conference space for briefings and meetings. Every element required coordination with military specifications and security protocols.</p>

        <p>Government and military projects demand understanding unique procurement requirements, security procedures, documentation standards, and quality expectations. We navigated federal contracting requirements while maintaining the efficiency and communication that makes Northway a valued partner for complex public sector work.</p>

        <h3>Project Highlights</h3>
        <ul style="line-height: 2; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
          <li>Complete renovation of WWII-era military building</li>
          <li>Structural upgrades ensuring long-term building integrity</li>
          <li>Modern office space for military operations</li>
          <li>Specialized facilities including secure gun room and locker areas</li>
          <li>Full compliance with military specifications and security requirements</li>
          <li>Coordination with federal contracting and oversight procedures</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Camp Williams Building 5020 demonstrates Northway Construction's ability to serve military and government clients with the professionalism, security awareness, and quality that these critical facilities demand.</p>
